        </m:mrow>
      </m:math>
    </equation>
    <para id="id326390"><emphasis effect="italics">and, therefore, from <link target-id="uid57"/>, the integral of the wavelet is zero.</emphasis></para><para id="id326400"><emphasis effect="italics">The fact that multiplying in the time domain by <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mo>-</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:msup></m:math> is equivalent to
shifting in the frequency domain by <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mi>π</m:mi></m:math> gives
<m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>ω</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mi>H</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>ω</m:mi><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:mi>π</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>.</emphasis></para></content>

